1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,950
In the last programming video,

2

00:00:01,950  -->  00:00:05,340
you saw how we could simulate draws from the null hypothesis,

3

00:00:05,340  -->  00:00:09,130
and that if our statistic was in the bulk of the distribution,

4

00:00:09,130  -->  00:00:13,485
this suggested that the statistic was likely from that null.

5

00:00:13,485  -->  00:00:17,649
However, if the statistic was farther out from the bulk of the distribution,

6

00:00:17,649  -->  00:00:22,765
this suggested that the null wasn't likely to have generated our statistic.

7

00:00:22,765  -->  00:00:28,000
Then you saw that we can calculate p-values based on the shaded region starting at

8

00:00:28,000  -->  00:00:32,927
the value of our observed statistic through the tail of the distribution,

9

00:00:32,927  -->  00:00:36,490
where the shaded region is dependent on our alternative.

10

00:00:36,490  -->  00:00:38,740
Based on the previous video,

11

00:00:38,740  -->  00:00:43,690
you had simulated values of the sampling distribution from the null, like this.

12

00:00:43,690  -->  00:00:45,850
Imagine that we have the alternative hypothesis

13

00:00:45,850  -->  00:00:48,586
that the population mean is greater than 70,

14

00:00:48,586  -->  00:00:51,580
then we could calculate the p-value as the proportion

15

00:00:51,580  -->  00:00:55,375
of the simulated draws that are larger than our sample mean.

16

00:00:55,375  -->  00:00:59,580
Here, you can see that that would give us a p-value of one.

17

00:00:59,580  -->  00:01:04,770
Remember, large p-value suggests that we shouldn't move away from the null hypothesis.

18

00:01:04,770  -->  00:01:10,724
In this case, that suggests that we should stay with the mean being less than 70.

19

00:01:10,724  -->  00:01:15,080
Here, we've calculated the null values that are greater than our sample mean.

20

00:01:15,080  -->  00:01:16,700
Since this is one,

21

00:01:16,700  -->  00:01:21,260
our p-value is large and therefore we wouldn't move away from the null hypothesis

22

00:01:21,260  -->  00:01:26,905
that suggests that our population mean is truly less than or equal to 70.

23

00:01:26,905  -->  00:01:31,265
If our new null and alternative hypotheses look like this instead,

24

00:01:31,265  -->  00:01:33,995
we would calculate our p-value a little differently.

25

00:01:33,995  -->  00:01:37,384
Here, because our alternative is less than 70,

26

00:01:37,384  -->  00:01:41,505
we would now look at the shaded region to the left of our statistic.

27

00:01:41,505  -->  00:01:44,140
This would change our p-value to the following.

28

00:01:44,140  -->  00:01:45,870
Now that our p-value is zero,

29

00:01:45,870  -->  00:01:50,848
this suggests that we reject the null hypothesis in favor of an alternative,

30

00:01:50,848  -->  00:01:55,400
suggesting that the population mean is less than 70.

31

00:01:55,400  -->  00:01:57,905
So if this was our null and alternative hypothesis,

32

00:01:57,905  -->  00:02:01,820
we would now want to look at the values that are more extreme

33

00:02:01,820  -->  00:02:06,124
than our sample mean in either direction away from the null hypothesis.

34

00:02:06,124  -->  00:02:08,355
That looks like this equation here.

35

00:02:08,355  -->  00:02:12,625
Let's take a look at where these values fall on the above histogram.

36

00:02:12,625  -->  00:02:16,325
You can see that if we were to shade more extreme than either of these regions,

37

00:02:16,325  -->  00:02:18,320
there are essentially no data points from

38

00:02:18,320  -->  00:02:21,345
our null hypothesis that fall outside of this region.

39

00:02:21,345  -->  00:02:23,780
Again, we would have evidence to suggest that

40

00:02:23,780  -->  00:02:29,030
the null hypothesized value did not generate our sample statistic.
